citeinfo.title: 2015 CENSUS BLOCK GROUPS IN FLORIDA (WITH SELECTED FIELDS FROM THE 2014-2018 AMERICAN COMMUNITY SURVEY)

descript.abstract:
This dataset contains the US Census Bureau 2015 Census Block Groups for the State of Florida with selected fields from the 2014-2018 American Community Survey (ACS). Some of the fields included in this dataset are total population, education, and housing and economic characteristics. This data is at the block group level. In addition, fields have been added and calculated.
The ACS was designed to replace the long-form of the decennial census. The ACS is a survey that releases data annually. ACS data are survey estimates distributed for 1-, 3-, and 5-year time periods. The 5-year estimates are the only time period estimates that provide data at the block group level. This data is designed for use within the Florida Department of Transportation?s Efficient Transportation Decision Making Process (ETDM). However, the subset of ACS fields included herein is useful for a variety of applications and uses. If you are looking for census block group data with the decennial census counts, please see the FGDL layer CENBLKGRP_2010.
descript.purpose: For the research and analysis of the 2007-2011 American Community Survey (ACS) at the Census Block Group geography level. The data contains selected fields from the 2007-2011 ACS. Census Block Groups are geographic entities made up of Census Blocks and that are contained within the same Census Tract. Block Groups generally contain between 600 and 3,000 people, with an optimum size of 1,500 people.

procstep.procdesc:
The 2015 TIGER line files were downloaded from the following site: https://www.census.gov/geo/maps-data/data/tiger-geodatabases.html date downloaded 12/13/16
The data was projected to Albers HPGN.
The American Community Survey data was downloaded from the Census Bureau in .csv format from: https://www2.census.gov/programs-surveys/acs/summary_file/2017/data/5_year_by_state/ date downloaded: 1/8/20
Changed name from tlgdb_2015_a_12_fl_931.gdb\Block_Group to CENACS_2018
A variety of GIS techniques including python scripting were used to parse, aggregate, and join the tabular demographic data to the spatial data. The result is a feature class with logically named fields that are made up of one or more census fields.
